FLASHCARDS.push(

  // h8-06 The French Revolution
  {id:"h8fc-06-A",islandId:"h8-06",
   front:"What were the Three Estates in Ancien Régime France?",
   back:"France was divided into three estates (social orders):\n\n1st Estate: the clergy (Church)\n2nd Estate: the nobility\n3rd Estate: everyone else — about 98% of the population, including peasants, urban workers and the bourgeoisie.\n\nOnly the 3rd Estate paid taxes, yet had almost no political power. This deep inequality was a major cause of revolution.",
   difficulty:1,category:"fact"},

  {id:"h8fc-06-B",islandId:"h8-06",
   front:"What happened on 14 July 1789 and why is it significant?",
   back:"On 14 July 1789, Parisian crowds stormed the Bastille fortress — a royal prison that symbolised royal tyranny.\n\nSignificance:\n• It marked the start of the French Revolution as a popular uprising.\n• The fortress held only 7 prisoners at the time, but its fall showed the power of the people against the monarchy.\n• 14 July is now Bastille Day — France's national holiday.",
   difficulty:1,category:"significance"},

  {id:"h8fc-06-C",islandId:"h8-06",
   front:"What was the Declaration of the Rights of Man (1789)?",
   back:"The Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen (August 1789) was a foundational document of the Revolution, stating:\n• All men are born free and equal in rights.\n• Citizens have rights to liberty, property, security and resistance to oppression.\n• Sovereignty belongs to the nation, not the king.\n\nInfluenced by Enlightenment thinkers (Rousseau, Voltaire) and the American Declaration of Independence. It did not, however, grant rights to women.",
   difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  {id:"h8fc-06-D",islandId:"h8-06",
   front:"What was the Reign of Terror (1793–94)?",
   back:"The Reign of Terror was a period of extreme political violence led by Maximilien Robespierre and the Committee of Public Safety.\n\nKey facts:\n• Approximately 17,000 people were officially executed by guillotine; tens of thousands more died in prison.\n• Anyone suspected of being an enemy of the Revolution could be arrested.\n• Robespierre himself was arrested and executed in July 1794 (Thermidorian Reaction).\n\nIt showed how revolutionary ideals of liberty could turn into dictatorship.",
   difficulty:2,category:"consequence"},

  {id:"h8fc-06-E",islandId:"h8-06",
   front:"How did Napoleon rise to power and what was his impact on Europe?",
   back:"Napoleon Bonaparte rose through military success during the Revolutionary Wars. In 1799 he seized power in the coup of 18 Brumaire, becoming First Consul, then Emperor in 1804.\n\nImpact on Europe:\n• Spread revolutionary ideas (legal equality, abolition of feudalism) across conquered territories via the Napoleonic Code.\n• Redrew the map of Europe through conquest.\n• Defeated at Waterloo (1815); exiled to St Helena.\n\nHis legacy is debated: liberator or dictator?",
   difficulty:3,category:"significance"},

  // h8-07 The Abolition of Slavery
  {id:"h8fc-07-A",islandId:"h8-07",
   front:"Who was Olaudah Equiano and why was he important to abolition?",
   back:"Olaudah Equiano (c.1745–1797) was an enslaved African who gained his freedom and published his autobiography, 'The Interesting Narrative' (1789).\n\nImportance:\n• His vivid first-hand account of the horrors of enslavement and the Middle Passage gave a human voice to the abolitionist cause.\n• The book was a bestseller and helped turn public opinion against slavery.\n• He was a founder member of the Sons of Africa, an abolitionist group.",
   difficulty:1,category:"significance"},

  {id:"h8fc-07-B",islandId:"h8-07",
   front:"What did the Abolition of the Slave Trade Act 1807 do, and what were its limits?",
   back:"The Abolition of the Slave Trade Act (1807):\n• Made it illegal for British ships to transport enslaved people.\n• Applied to the slave trade, not to slavery itself.\n\nLimitations:\n• People already enslaved in British colonies remained enslaved.\n• Many slave traders continued illegally.\n• Full legal freedom for enslaved people in most British colonies did not come until the Slavery Abolition Act 1833, which took effect on 1 August 1834 (with a further apprenticeship period until 1838).",
   difficulty:2,category:"consequence"},

  {id:"h8fc-07-C",islandId:"h8-07",
   front:"What role did William Wilberforce play in the abolition movement?",
   back:"William Wilberforce (1759–1833) was a Member of Parliament who became the leading political voice for abolition.\n\nKey contributions:\n• Introduced abolition bills in Parliament repeatedly from 1789.\n• Worked with the Society for Effecting the Abolition of the Slave Trade (founded 1787).\n• His persistence paid off with the Slave Trade Act 1807.\n• He died just days after hearing that the Slavery Abolition Act 1833 had passed.\n\nHe worked alongside Thomas Clarkson, Granville Sharp and formerly enslaved activists.",
   difficulty:2,category:"fact"},

  {id:"h8fc-07-D",islandId:"h8-07",
   front:"What was the significance of the Slavery Abolition Act 1833?",
   back:"The Slavery Abolition Act 1833:\n• Abolished slavery throughout most of the British Empire.\n• Came into force on 1 August 1834.\n• Approximately 800,000 enslaved people were freed.\n\nControversial aspects:\n• The British government paid £20 million in compensation — but to the enslaveholders, not to the freed people.\n• A period of 'apprenticeship' kept many formerly enslaved people tied to their enslaver until 1838.\n• The compensation debt was only fully repaid by UK taxpayers in 2015.",
   difficulty:3,category:"significance"},

  {id:"h8fc-07-E",islandId:"h8-07",
   front:"How did enslaved people resist slavery?",
   back:"Enslaved people resisted in many ways:\n\nActive resistance:\n• Large-scale rebellions: Tacky's War (Jamaica, 1760), the Haitian Revolution (1791–1804), Sam Sharpe's Rebellion (Jamaica, 1831–32).\n• The Haitian Revolution led to Haiti becoming the first Black republic in 1804.\n\nDay-to-day resistance:\n• Working slowly, breaking tools, feigning illness, preserving cultural traditions.\n\nLegal action:\n• The Somerset Case (1772) — Granville Sharp helped James Somerset gain freedom in England, establishing that slavery had no legal basis in English law.",
   difficulty:2,category:"cause"},

  // h8-08 World War I
  {id:"h8fc-08-A",islandId:"h8-08",
   front:"What does MAIN stand for and how did each factor cause WWI?",
   back:"MAIN summarises the long-term causes of World War I:\n\nMilitarism — European powers, especially Germany, had been building up large armies and navies (Anglo-German naval race).\nAlliances — Europe was divided into two armed camps: Triple Alliance (Germany, Austria-Hungary, Italy) vs Triple Entente (France, Russia, Britain).\nImperialism — rivalry over colonies created tensions between powers.\nNationalism — desire for independence (e.g. Slavs in the Balkans) and national pride raised tensions dramatically.\n\nThe assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand in June 1914 was the immediate trigger.",
   difficulty:1,category:"cause"},

  {id:"h8fc-08-B",islandId:"h8-08",
   front:"What were the conditions in the trenches on the Western Front?",
   back:"Trench warfare on the Western Front (Belgium and northern France):\n\nConditions:\n• Waterlogged, muddy trenches — soldiers suffered from trench foot.\n• Constant threat from enemy fire, artillery and gas attacks.\n• Rats, lice and disease were widespread.\n• 'No Man's Land' — the deadly ground between opposing trenches.\n\nKey features:\n• Stalemate developed quickly as neither side could advance.\n• Soldiers rotated between front-line, support and reserve trenches.\n• 'Going over the top' during an offensive was extremely dangerous.",
   difficulty:1,category:"fact"},

  {id:"h8fc-08-C",islandId:"h8-08",
   front:"What happened on the first day of the Battle of the Somme (1 July 1916)?",
   back:"The Battle of the Somme began on 1 July 1916 and was one of the bloodiest days in British military history.\n\nKey facts:\n• The British army suffered approximately 57,000 casualties on the first day alone, including about 19,240 killed.\n• The battle lasted until November 1916 with over 1 million total casualties on all sides.\n• The British used tanks for the first time at the Somme (September 1916).\n\nThe battle showed the devastating cost of industrial-scale warfare but also led to new tactics being developed.",
   difficulty:2,category:"fact"},

  {id:"h8fc-08-D",islandId:"h8-08",
   front:"What were the main terms of the Treaty of Versailles (1919)?",
   back:"The Treaty of Versailles (signed June 1919) imposed harsh terms on Germany:\n\nThe 'BRAT' terms:\nBlame — Article 231 (War Guilt Clause): Germany accepted sole blame for the war.\nReparations — Germany had to pay £6.6 billion in reparations.\nArmy — German armed forces were severely limited (100,000 soldiers, no air force, limited navy).\nTerritory — Germany lost 13% of its land, including Alsace-Lorraine to France and the Polish Corridor.\n\nMany Germans felt the treaty was deeply unjust, which contributed to the rise of extremist parties including the Nazis.",
   difficulty:2,category:"consequence"},

  {id:"h8fc-08-E",islandId:"h8-08",
   front:"What was the impact of WWI on women's roles in Britain?",
   back:"World War I significantly changed women's roles in Britain:\n\nDuring the war:\n• Women took on roles previously held by men: munitions workers, bus conductresses, nurses, land workers (Women's Land Army).\n• Over 900,000 women worked in munitions by 1918.\n\nPolitical impact:\n• Women's contribution to the war effort strengthened the argument for women's suffrage.\n• The Representation of the People Act 1918 gave the vote to women aged 30 and over who met property qualifications.\n• Full equal voting rights came with the Equal Franchise Act 1928.",
   difficulty:3,category:"significance"},

  // h8-09 The Suffragettes
  {id:"h8fc-09-A",islandId:"h8-09",
   front:"What is the difference between the Suffragists (NUWSS) and the Suffragettes (WSPU)?",
   back:"Suffragists — NUWSS (National Union of Women's Suffrage Societies):\n• Founded 1897 by Millicent Fawcett.\n• Used peaceful, constitutional methods: petitions, leaflets, meetings, lobbying MPs.\n• Believed in gradual persuasion.\n\nSuffragettes — WSPU (Women's Social and Political Union):\n• Founded 1903 by Emmeline Pankhurst.\n• Used militant direct action: chaining themselves to railings, window-smashing, arson, hunger strikes.\n• Motto: 'Deeds not Words'.\n\nBoth groups shared the same goal — votes for women — but disagreed on tactics.",
   difficulty:1,category:"concept"},

  {id:"h8fc-09-B",islandId:"h8-09",
   front:"Who was Emily Wilding Davison and what happened at the 1913 Derby?",
   back:"Emily Wilding Davison was a committed Suffragette who had been imprisoned and force-fed multiple times.\n\nAt the Epsom Derby (4 June 1913) she stepped onto the racecourse and was struck by King George V's horse, Anmer. She died four days later.\n\nHistorical debate:\n• Some historians argue she intended to die as a martyr.\n• Others believe she was attempting to attach a Suffragette banner to the horse.\n• Her death brought worldwide attention to the suffrage cause.\n• Thousands lined the streets at her funeral procession in London.",
   difficulty:2,category:"significance"},

  {id:"h8fc-09-C",islandId:"h8-09",
   front:"What was the Cat and Mouse Act (1913) and why was it introduced?",
   back:"The Prisoners (Temporary Discharge for Ill Health) Act 1913 — known as the Cat and Mouse Act:\n\nContext: Imprisoned Suffragettes went on hunger strike; the government responded with force-feeding, which caused public outrage.\n\nHow it worked:\n• Hunger-striking prisoners were released when they became dangerously ill.\n• Once recovered, they were re-arrested to serve the remainder of their sentence.\n• Critics said the government was 'playing cat and mouse' with women.\n\nPurpose: to prevent Suffragette deaths in prison (which would create martyrs) without ending force-feeding.",
   difficulty:2,category:"cause"},

  {id:"h8fc-09-D",islandId:"h8-09",
   front:"What did the Representation of the People Acts of 1918 and 1928 achieve?",
   back:"Representation of the People Act 1918:\n• Gave the vote to women aged 30 and over who met property qualifications (or whose husbands did).\n• Also gave ALL men over 21 the vote (removing property qualifications for men).\n• About 8.4 million women gained the vote.\n\nEqual Franchise Act 1928:\n• Extended the vote to ALL women aged 21 and over on the same terms as men.\n• The 'Flapper Vote' — approximately 5 million more women were enfranchised.\n• Britain finally had full adult suffrage.\n\nMillicent Fawcett attended the signing of the 1928 Act aged 81.",
   difficulty:1,category:"fact"},

  {id:"h8fc-09-E",islandId:"h8-09",
   front:"Why were women denied the vote before 1918? What arguments were used against suffrage?",
   back:"Arguments used against women's suffrage:\n\n• Women were considered too emotional or irrational to vote wisely.\n• A woman's place was in the home — the 'separate spheres' ideology.\n• Women did not fight in wars, so should not have a say in affairs of state.\n• Giving women the vote would undermine the family and social order.\n• Many women themselves (at first) opposed suffrage.\n\nNote: working-class men without property were also denied the vote before 1832 (Reform Act) and 1918, so suffrage was a wider democratic issue, not only about gender.",
   difficulty:3,category:"cause"},

  // h8-10 The Inter-War Years
  {id:"h8fc-10-A",islandId:"h8-10",
   front:"Why did the Weimar Republic face such serious problems after 1919?",
   back:"The Weimar Republic (Germany's new democratic government, 1919–1933) faced severe challenges:\n\n• 'Stab in the back' myth — many Germans wrongly blamed civilian politicians (not the military) for Germany's defeat in WWI.\n• The Republic was associated with the hated Treaty of Versailles.\n• Hyperinflation (1923): reparations payments and the French occupation of the Ruhr led to economic collapse — a loaf of bread cost billions of marks.\n• Political violence from both left (Spartacist uprising, 1919) and right (Kapp Putsch, 1920; Beer Hall Putsch, 1923).\n\nThese crises made extremist parties, including the Nazis, seem appealing to desperate voters.",
   difficulty:2,category:"cause"},

  {id:"h8fc-10-B",islandId:"h8-10",
   front:"What was the League of Nations and why did it fail?",
   back:"The League of Nations (founded 1920) was an international organisation established to maintain peace and prevent another world war — proposed by US President Woodrow Wilson as part of his 14 Points.\n\nStrengths: settled some disputes, improved working conditions (ILO), helped refugees.\n\nWeaknesses:\n• The USA never joined (Senate refused to ratify).\n• No permanent armed force of its own — relied on member states.\n• Germany and the USSR were initially excluded.\n• Sanctions were ineffective — e.g. against Italy's invasion of Abyssinia (1935).\n• Decisions required unanimity, making action slow.\n\nIt ultimately failed to prevent World War II.",
   difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  {id:"h8fc-10-C",islandId:"h8-10",
   front:"How did Hitler rise to power in Germany between 1929 and 1933?",
   back:"Key steps in Hitler's rise to power:\n\n1929 Wall Street Crash — the Great Depression caused mass unemployment in Germany (over 6 million by 1932), making voters desperate for radical solutions.\n1932 — The Nazi Party (NSDAP) became the largest party in the Reichstag in elections.\nJanuary 1933 — President Hindenburg appointed Hitler as Chancellor.\nFebruary 1933 — Reichstag Fire: used by Nazis to justify the Reichstag Fire Decree, suspending civil liberties.\nMarch 1933 — Enabling Act gave Hitler dictatorial powers.\n\nHitler exploited genuine grievances (Versailles, economic crisis) and used propaganda, fear and violence.",
   difficulty:2,category:"cause"},

  {id:"h8fc-10-D",islandId:"h8-10",
   front:"What was appeasement and why did Britain follow this policy in the 1930s?",
   back:"Appeasement was the policy of making concessions to an aggressive power to avoid war.\n\nKey example: the Munich Agreement (September 1938) — Britain (Neville Chamberlain) and France allowed Hitler to annex the Sudetenland region of Czechoslovakia. Chamberlain returned claiming 'peace for our time'.\n\nReasons for appeasement:\n• Horror at the prospect of another world war after WWI.\n• Belief that Germany's grievances over Versailles were partly justified.\n• Britain was not militarily ready for war.\n• Fear of communism — some saw Hitler as a barrier against the Soviet Union.\n\nCritics (Winston Churchill) argued appeasement only emboldened Hitler.",
   difficulty:2,category:"concept"},

  {id:"h8fc-10-E",islandId:"h8-10",
   front:"What was the Great Depression and how did it contribute to the rise of extremism?",
   back:"The Great Depression began with the Wall Street Crash (October 1929) in the USA and spread globally.\n\nEffects:\n• Mass unemployment worldwide — in Germany, over 6 million were unemployed by 1932.\n• Banks collapsed; businesses closed; poverty widespread.\n\nPolitical consequences:\n• Democratic governments seemed unable to solve the crisis.\n• Extremist parties offered simple answers and scapegoats.\n• The Nazis gained votes rapidly in Germany; fascism grew in Italy (Mussolini had taken power in 1922).\n• In Britain, Oswald Mosley founded the British Union of Fascists (1932).\n\nEconomic despair made ordinary people willing to support radical, anti-democratic movements.",
   difficulty:3,category:"consequence"}

);

